    "summary": "The Yamato Period (c. 250–710 AD) marks the emergence of a centralized Japanese state under the Yamato clan, who consolidated political authority over the Japanese archipelago and established the imperial dynasty that has continued, at least in nominal form, to the present day — making the Japanese imperial house the oldest continuous monarchy in the world. The Yamato state developed from the Kofun period ([[event:2090|Kofun Period]]) and was deeply influenced by continental contacts with Korea and China, absorbing Chinese writing, Buddhism ([[event:2096|Buddhism spread to Japan]]), Confucian governance concepts, and administrative models.\n\nThe Yamato kings (later emperors) used Chinese-style governance, diplomacy, and prestige objects to legitimize their rule — sending embassies to the Chinese courts, receiving Buddhist texts and priests, and adopting Chinese titles and ceremonial practices. The Nihon Shoki and Kojiki (Japan's earliest chronicles, compiled in the 8th century) record Yamato royal genealogy and mythology, including the legendary divine descent of the imperial house from the sun goddess Amaterasu. The Yamato period saw the construction of vast keyhole-shaped burial mounds (kofun), adoption of Buddhism as a state religion, and the compilation of the first Japanese legal codes — transforming Japan from a loose confederation of clans into a centralized state modeled on Tang China.",
    "wikipedia_url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Yamato_period",
